options.tex:
\begin{align}
\frac{dy}{dx} &= \underbrace{\frac{y}{x} - \csc\frac{y}{x}}_{F(x)} \\
\text{where } F(\lambda x) &= F(x) 
\end{align} 
%text


Therefore, the given differential equation is 
\underline\text{homogenous}
%

\begin{align}
\frac{dy}{dx} - \frac{1}{x}y &=  - \csc\frac{y}{x}
\end{align} 
%text


The above is of the form 
\[ \qquad \frac{dy}{dx} + P(x)\cdot\frac{dy}{dx} = Q(x) \]
Hence, it must be a \underline\text{linear} differential equation.
%

reason.tex:
\begin{align}
y = v\cdot x &\implies \frac{dy}{dx} = v + x\cdot\frac{dv}{dx} \\
\therefore \frac{dy}{dx} - \frac{y}{x} &= -\csc\frac{y}{x}\\
\implies \left(v+x \frac{dv}{dx}\right) -v &= -\csc v \\
\text{or }x\frac{dv}{dx} = -\csc v &\implies \frac{dx}{x} = -\sin v\cdot dv 
\end{align}
